<TEXT>
at first glance the republicans appear to 
have gathered in hostile political territory but an overwhelming 
democratic registration edge masks growing republican strength in 
louisiana 
new orleans mayor sidney barthelemy a jesse jackson democrat 
and a vice chairman of the national democratic party leads a city 
where registered democrats outnumber registered republicans 189741 
to 34853 
statewide there are 2146867 registered voters and only about 
322000 of them 15 percent are republicans 
in the legislature there are 23 republicans among the 144 
members 
republicans have been scarce in louisiana since reconstruction 
populist democrats like huey long who taxed oil companies to 
provide free state services further cemented the democrats hold 
on the state when blacks became a voting force as a result of the 
civil rights movement democrats broadened their base despite 
occasional defections by white voters to states rights candidates 
but things are looking up for the louisiana gop republicans 
have won five of the last eight presidential races in the state 
half of louisianas eight us house members are republicans now 
ten years ago republican registration was just 79900 and the 
longstanding joke was that they could hold the state convention in 
a telephone booth 
chinks in the democrats louisiana fortress first were seen more 
than 30 years ago when the state went for dwight d eisenhower in 
the 1956 presidential race in later years louisianas electoral 
votes went to republicans barry goldwater in 1964 richard nixon in 
1972 and ronald reagan in 1980 and 1984 
in 1972 dave treen after three losing campaigns became the 
first republican to win a congressional seat in louisiana since 
reconstruction 
treen later became the first republican governor since 
reconstruction when he was elected to the post in 1979 ironically 
he was helped by a law the democrats had pushed to help themselves 
the unique open primary law 
all candidates from all parties run in one election if no 
candidate wins a majority the top two finishers regardless of 
party face a runoff 
the law was designed to keep democrats from exhausting their 
energies and campaign funds in volatile primary battles against 
each other only to face a single wellfinanced republican in a 
general election 
but since anyone could vote regardless of party registration 
it allowed conservative democrats to cross party lines and vote 
for republicans 
 
in addition to gop house gains former republican rep henson 
moore forced democrat john breaux to wage a tough comefrombehind 
battle in 1986 to keep democratic control of the senate seat left 
vacant by the retirement of russell long a powerful democrat and 
son of huey long 
all is not roses for the republicans in louisiana even with the 
open primary 
for example democrats remain so strong that the planners for 
the 1988 gop convention yanked democratic mayor barthelemy off the 
schedule for their nationally televised opening night ceremonies so 
his welcoming remarks would be made during a less conspicuous 
morning session 
after his 1986 loss to breaux moore said he did not think a 
republican could beat a democrat in a headtohead match 
that was three years after treen was overwhelmingly defeated 
when popular twoterm governor edwin edwards a democrat returned 
to politics after a fouryear hiatus 
and although edwards political fortunes fell with the price of 
oil and the states poor economy it took another democrat buddy 
roemer to drive edwards out of office in last years election 
roemer came from the back of a fiveman pack to beat edwards and 
rep robert livingston the republican who had been considered a 
sure bet for a runoff with edwards 
treen believes the louisiana gops growing strength results in 
part from the tenacity of republicans like him who ran against 
enormous odds in the 1950s and 1960s 
if i had the wisdom of my present age which is 60 when i ran 
for congress i probably would not have run for congress back in 
1962 he said but he does not regret it 
that race led to the 64 race and the 68 race and 
eventually to the race i won in 1972 
</TEXT>
