<TEXT>
gov michael dukakis may not invoke executive 
privilege to keep documents from the public the massachusetts 
supreme court ruled today 
the unanimous decision came in the case of two homosexual men 
who are challenging the dukakis administrations decision to remove 
two young boys from foster care in their boston home but it could 
affect other issues 
the democratic presidential nominees administration has cited 
executive privilege in a number of areas to avoid having to 
disclose internal memos and other sensitive papers opponents of 
plans to put a new prison in new braintree are seeking to force 
disclosure of documents showing how the site was chosen 
there is no such privilege in massachusetts the court said 
in an opinion written by chief justice edward f hennessey 
the justices said they found no justification in the state 
constitution or state law for withholding government documents 
they said the creation of laws rights or privileges was a policy 
issue best left to the legislature 
had the framers of our governments structure intended to 
recognize in our constitution an executive privilege it is 
reasonable to expect that they would expressly have created one 
they said 
its a victory for accountability and open government said 
anthony m doniger attorney for donald babets and david jean 
the public now has a right to know how its government comes to 
its decisions that is a good thing in a democracy 
spokesmen for dukakis were traveling with him to central 
massachusetts and were not immediately available for comment 
the case began in 1985 when the dukakis administration removed 
two youngsters then aged 3 and 22 months from babets and jean 
after a study the department of social services promulgated rules 
for placing foster children that gave lowest priority to homosexual 
individuals who lacked experience as parents and gave first 
priority to married couples with children 
babets and jean filed suit in suffolk superior court in january 
1986 challenging the legality of the rules the suit named dukakis 
human services secretary philip johnston and dss commissioner sandy 
matava as defendants although dukakis was later dropped as a named 
defendant 
babets and jean argued that the policy discriminated and 
violated their constitutional rights to equal protection free 
association and privacy 
during the trial lawyers for babets and jean asked judge james 
p lynch jr to order the dukakis administration to divulge certain 
documents relating to the policymaking process after hearings and 
an inspection of the documents lynch ordered the government to 
surrender them but lynch stayed his order and referred the 
constitutional questions to the appellate courts 
todays ruling specifically affirms lynchs order apparently 
forcing the state to release the requested documents 
