<TEXT>
state health officials have canceled a 17 
million contract with an ad agency to produce youthoriented 
nosmoking commercials because the agency merged with another which 
has a tobacco company account 
the incident shows how long the tentacles of the tobacco 
industry are said kathy harty manager of the state health 
departments section on nonsmoking and health 
the campbellmithun agency based in minneapolis recently 
merged with new yorkbased william esty which has a 35 million 
account with brown amp williamson tobacco co 
campbellmithun which had a twoyear contract with the state 
developed and produced television and radio spots that have been 
broadcast regularly around the state since january one shows 
students falling over dominofashion from the bad breath of a 
teenage girl smoker another highlights the smelly odor left in 
smokers clothes 
the campaign rather than focusing on longterm health risks of 
smoking emphasized the lowered personal attractiveness and social 
isolation of the smoker 
the us department of health and human services recently began 
airing animated public service ads with a similar tone 
characterizing smokers as buttheads and pariahs 
harty said friday that campbellmithun would be replaced by the 
martinwilliams agency of minneapolis for at least two years 
the contract with campbellmithun had just been renewed when its 
merger with esty was announced last month she added 
the campbellmithun advertisements have been very effective 
harty said based on measurements of audience reach and recall 
campbellmithun made deft use of the states limited 
mediabuying budget obtaining a significant number of free spots 
along with those it bought she said 
paula baldwin a spokeswoman for what now is campbellmithun 
esty said the move was an extremely difficult decision to reach 
but it was an amicable one we remain very very proud of the work 
we did 
esty and the former campbellmithun agencies are owned by the 
new yorkbased saatchi amp saatchi dfs inc 
mary gustafson a martinwilliams spokeswoman said the agencys 
projections indicate very little likelihood of landing a 
tobaccolinked account 
