a fire broke out monday on the 51st floor of the 
empire state building forcing dozens of office workers to evacuate 
the 102story tower and officials said the second blaze there in 
three days was suspicious 
the blaze which began in a batch of carpets discarded in a 
stairwell produced heavy smoke but caused only minor damage to the 
landmark skyscraper firefighters doused the fire about a half hour 
after it began 
authorities declined to say why the fire was declared 
suspicious but fire commissioner joseph bruno said the 
investigation would include why 10 rolledup carpets were stashed 
in the stairwell 
chief robert manson the deputy borough commander who commanded 
fire forces at the scene in last fridays fire as well as the one 
monday said he had found nothing to link the two blazes 
department spokesman john mulligan said 
one woman in the building fell but declined medical treatment 
and a second was removed to bellevue hospital with possible cardiac 
arrest one firefighter was sent to bellevue for treatment of smoke 
inhalation and heat exhaustion 
the temperature was about 94 and rising at the time of the fire 
which was reported at 1134 am and extinguished at 1212 pm 
an offduty firefighter visiting his brother discovered the fire 
and helped to put it out mulligan said 
between 50 to 100 tenants on the five floors of the towers 
midsection floors 51 through 56 were evacuated because of the 
smoke said frank corbin a management spokesman for the building 
the fire department initially reported that the fire started in 
an electrical conduit in a 50th floor stairwell later the 
department attributed the cause to the burning carpets 
on friday a fire broke out in an 86th floor shaftway after it 
was brought under control firefighters discovered that it had 
climbed up to the 102nd floor 
the popular observation decks at both those levels had to be 
closed and some 1500 tourists evacuated 
in addition to forcing other evacuations because of smoke the 
fire friday interrupted broadcasting for several hours by eight fm 
radio stations whose antennae are atop the building 
