<TEXT>
more than 300 miners monday protested 
dangerous working conditions and the lockout of three solidarity 
leaders at a copper mine 
jacek kuron a spokesman for the outlawed union said workers 
staged a rally at the rudna mine in southwestern poland after 
managers failed to fulfill promises made after a strike in may 
the workers also demanded that the solidarity leaders members 
of a commission fighting for improved safety at the mine be 
allowed to return to work kuron said the three men have not been 
fired but were ordered to turn in their identity cards saturday 
the rudna copper mine has been the scene of frequent unrest 
managers ended the strike in may by agreeing to improve safety but 
failed to meet mondays deadline for implementing the changes 
kuron said the miners planned another rally tuesday 
solidarity activists say the miners are working in dangerously 
high temperatures with poor ventilation 
safety issues have not been addressed by the officially 
sanctioned trade union at rudna however that group has pressed 
for higher pay 
kuron said the miners also demanded the right to form 
independent trade unions solidarity has been suppressed since 
1981 when polands communist leaders imposed martial law it was 
banned by parliament the next year 
</TEXT>
