<TEXT>
health officials are premature in embracing 
programs to trace sexual and needlesharing partners of people 
infected with the aids virus researchers said monday 
such programs are required by the federal government as a 
condition of grants to states for aids programs 
but there is little evidence such programs curb the spread of 
the virus the researchers said at the annual meeting of the 
american psychological association 
in response a government public health expert defended the 
programs as a way to get education to people a high risk of 
infection 
we have to try and make education work said russ havlak of 
the federal centers for disease control 
the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome can be 
spread by sex or sharing of needles used to inject drugs one goal 
of notification is to limit the spread of infection by uncovering 
people who do not realize they carry the virus and persuading them 
to act accordingly 
but evidence is lacking that notification affects virus spread 
said edmund dejowski of rutgers university so it is premature to 
adopt widespread notification he said 
cdcs havlak said that while the brief counseling that surrounds 
a notification will not be enough to make a person change his 
behavior that counseling is only the beginning 
longterm counseling and support are needed to bring about 
behavior change he said many parts of the country have yet to 
develop such programs he added 
dejowski also said the workings of some notification programs 
raise questions about the rights of notified people 
one citys notifiers ask to draw blood for a test from the 
person at the time he is notified he said the contacted person 
having just heard overwhelming information from a stranger may 
not be able to properly consider that request dejowski said 
havlak called the point arguable but said the notifiers offer 
onthespot testing only as an option distraught people are 
offered crisis intervention help rather than being forced to decide 
on the blood test he said 
dejowski also criticized pending federal legislation that would 
make states and local governments allow notification of spouses to 
be done by medical personnel such notification lacks the control 
and accountability of programs by public agencies he said 
and there is no guarantee that a doctor nurse or other medical 
professional would have the training and sensitivity to deliver the 
news properly he said 
havlak said he knows of no state that now prevents doctors from 
doing such notifications doctors can get help from state health 
departments if they wish he said 
