<TEXT>
the police chief monday yielded to pressure 
from civil rights leaders and rescinded a policy requiring officers 
to randomly stop black youths in a racially mixed neighborhood 
chief martin felker issued an order july 8 that police stop and 
question groups of black teenagers in what he called an effort to 
end racial violence in old west end neighborhood 
the procedure was implemented to address a series of crimes 
that had been committed felker said in a statement monday 
afternoon unfortunately the focus of the directive has been 
perceived as racially motivated instead of the intent of focusing 
on the suspects involved 
the statement apparently was issued to clarify reports earlier 
monday that felker had just dropped the word black from his 
directive the statement said he had rescinded the order and 
directed his officers to return to normal procedures of stopping 
people only if police believe reasonable cause exists 
felkers decision followed meetings with the president of the 
toledo chapter of the national association for the advancement of 
colored people city officials and neighborhood residents 
a group of black lawyers hailed felkers decision but said a 1 
million federal lawsuit against the city would not be withdrawn 
the suit will continue and we expect more plaintiffs to join 
us the policy was patently racist said lafayette tolliver vice 
president of the thurgood marshall law association 
the group filed the lawsuit friday on behalf of walter wade jr 
a black teenager who was followed and stopped by police in front 
of his house but never charged with a crime 
the lawsuit said the policy violates the constitutional 
protections against illegal search and seizure 
us district judge john potter rejected the groups request for 
a temporary restraining order after learning felker had rescinded 
his directive 
blacks make up about 17 percent of the citys population of 
340000 
