<TEXT>
puerto rican speakers showed their deep 
divisions at the united nations monday over whether statehood 
independence or keeping the islands status as a us commonwealth 
was the answer to its economic woes 
the united nations decolonization committee is holding hearings 
this week on puerto ricos status athough the united states 
already has rejected the committee as antiamerican 
a diplomat on the committee speaking on condition of anonymity 
said the committee probably will issue a resolution wednesday 
calling for selfdetermination for puerto rico 
william felice from an organization called the international 
league for the rights and liberation of peoples said puerto rico 
has become poorer than any us state and should be granted 
independence 
but manuel medina a member of a group called puerto ricans for 
statehood inc told the committee puerto rico would benefit more 
by achieving statehood medina said the island still could preserve 
its spanish culture 
other speakers said the united states was actively trying to 
block the proindependence movement 
cuban ambassador oscar oramasoliva introduced a resolution 
which noted allegations that the federal bureau of investigation 
was using surveillance to keep track of puerto rican independence 
activists 
the united states seized puerto rico in 1898 during the 
spanishamerican war puerto ricans are us citizens 
in 1952 puerto rican voters overwhelmingly passed a referendum 
favoring commonwealth status and the following year the general 
assembly removed puerto rico from its list of colonies 
since 1973 the un decolonization committee has adopted 
numerous resolutions calling puerto rico an illegal colony and 
demanding selfdetermination for its people 
the united states rejected those resolutions as interference in 
us internal affairs and in 1971 walked off the committee saying 
it had an antiamerican bias 
prostatehood speakers told the committee monday that 95 percent 
of the islands voters rejected independence in a 1984 election and 
that the solution to poverty is to make puerto rico the 51st us 
state 
jan susler of the national lawyers guild described the us 
attitude toward the commonwealth as colonial saying 
proindependence advocates are added to blacklists compiled by the 
fbi and shared with the puerto rican police 
she said washington used the grand jury system to compel friends 
and family members of proindependence advocates to testify about 
their activities or face jail a method to politically intern 
puerto rican independence activists 
