<TEXT>
the charred skeletons of a once 
magnificent city center still dominate dresdens patchwork skyline 
of hasty postwar renewal and piecemeal restoration 
city planners acknowledge and many dresden residents complain 
that the pace of restoration has been slowed because east germanys 
capital east berlin has been given priority in rebuilding efforts 
dresden known as the german florence before its almost 
total destruction in two days of allied firebombing raids in 1945 
is today a city of stark often brutal contrasts 
viewed from the far end of the old augustus bridge over the elbe 
river the meticulously rebuilt semper opera house roman catholic 
cathedral and zwinger gallery stand next to the bombedout and 
scorched ruins of the once majestic royal palace 
despite initial restoration efforts the palaces crumbling and 
roofless facades remain in large part home for birds and overgrown 
vegetation 
featureless sovietstyle housing and commercial blocks erected 
after world war ii now dominate the citys main thoroughfares and 
plazas interspersed with vast and idle spaces long since cleared 
of rubble 
most of the citys once fabled baroque turrets and spires are 
gone 
nevertheless city officials are fiercely proud of the 
restoration projects undertaken in recent years 
but they say much work has been slowed because of lack of 
resources 
many grumbling dresdeners blame the restoration delays and the 
widespread deterioration of many buildings that survived on poor 
planning and breakneck efforts to spruce up east berlin 
more than 20000 construction workers were ordered to east 
berlin last year to work on massive building projects as communist 
party officials strove to compete with west berlins glitter during 
the citys 750th anniversary celebrations 
east german officials in an effort to make east berlin a 
showcase have diverted building materials and workers to the 
capital for years leaving many provincial cities to struggle to 
find the means to restore thousands of crumbling buildings 
karlheinz seltmann an official in dresdens city 
administration responsible for culture defended the allocation of 
resources 
the capital city is the capital city he said 
others say the city and the nation faced an awesome 
reconstruction task after world war ii 
you have to remember that this city was raised from 15 million 
cubic meters of total ruin said manfred bachmann director 
general of dresdens 11 state musuems referring to the firestorm 
that devastated the city feb 1314 1945 
the destruction of dresden in the final days of the war has 
prompted debate among military historians about the necessity of 
the raids at a time when the soviet army was already rapidly 
advancing into nazi germany 
the city a communications and rail link was swollen with 
refugees and estimates of the death toll have ranged from 35000 to 
more than 135000 
the city and its destruction figured prominently in author kurt 
vonnegut jrs internationally acclaimed 1969 novel 
slaughterhouse five 
bachmann said the devastation did not break the citys will to 
survive 
dresden residents turned out to help rebuild the zwinger 
gallery when many of them still had no homes to return to 
he added that the city had accomplished much despite the 
subsequent shortages 
he said city pride and a deeprooted sense of cultural tradition 
has helped dresden recover much of its reputation as a city once 
legendary for its art architecture and music 
most of dresdens art treasures escaped wartime destruction 
bachmann said because they were hidden by the nazis in more than 
50 locations around the state of saxony many were discovered in 
poor condition in a damp mine shaft by soviet troops bachmann said 
the russians preserved them and returned them to us 
he said more than 1240 paintings were returned but about 500 
works are still missing including two rembrandts 
the treasures of the saxon royalty known as the gruene 
gewoelbe also survived the the war intact and are on display at 
the state art gallery 
the collection contains more than 3000 stunningly crafted works 
in gold silver ivory ebony amber brass and bronze many are 
lavishly decorated with precious stones 
bachmann said he hoped shortages that have slowed restoration of 
the royal palace can be overcome and that work can be completed by 
the turn of the century 
the palace will be the repository of many of the citys art 
treasures now in storage because of a lack of gallery space 
but some of the citys most dramatic restoration achievements 
are already in peril because of air pollution 
heavilyladen diesel trucks and cars using oillaced gasoline 
roar past theater square belching clouds of exhaust fumes around 
the opera and zwinger gallery coating the buildings with a film of 
grimy black soot 
emissions from a coalfired power plant not far away also 
threaten the sandstone and granite facades 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

