<DOCNO> AP880815-0242 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when the new us immigration 
law went into effect last year this town in durango cattle country 
500 miles south of el paso texas feared for its future 
for nearly half a century it had supplied mexicans who worked 
legally or illegally in the united states and sent home the dollars 
that helped keep the town going 
but the catastrophe santa maria del oro braced for 14 months ago 
hasnt happened 
thousands of dollars still pour in every day in money orders 
sent by residents relatives working most of them illegally in 
the united states 
mayor epifanio carreon had feared the flow of dollars would dry 
up and worse hundreds of young men would come home looking for 
jobs that dont exist 
we would have seen at least some economic affects of the law 
by now but everything is totally normal carreon says now 
the dollar continues being the most important source of income 
in this region said roberto acosta assistant manager of banco 
internacional the only bank in the area people that cashes dollar 
checks 
some people returned because of fear before they knew what was 
going to happen with the law but now things are back to normal 
one young man in town said however hes waiting to see what 
happens with the law the us immigration control and reform act 
before he attempts his first crossing 
if it werent for the law id already be in los angeles 
said rocky rocha 18 who just graduated from a technical school 
here 
he said two of his brothers already there had applied for 
amnesty under the us law and fear theyll lose out if they harbor 
him as an illegal alien 
if my brothers will let me ill go in spite of the law 
said rocha here you work so hard and you dont make much 
santa maria del oro has supplied the us labor market with a 
steady stream of workers since world war ii 
many residents went to the united states as farm workers under 
the us bracero program of 1942 said mayor carreon by now some 
have gained us citizenship or legal residency 
by the time the program was dropped in 1964 many local 
residents had grown accustomed to having a steady job and earning 
dollars 
besides said carreon the local gold and mining operations were 
winding down and there wasnt much left to do here but work in the 
fields or raise cattle the only major employer around these days 
is a lumber company which has about 300 workers 
miguel angel salinas the municipal clerk estimates that more 
than 30 percent of the towns 14000 people still go back and forth 
to jobs in the united states 
authorities estimate the percentage of people on surrounding 
farms and ranches with relatives working in the united states is as 
high or even higher 
carreon said the steady flow of dollars as much as 60000 a 
week has helped santa maria del oro weather mexicos 6yearold 
economic crisis 
indeed by mexican standards santa maria del oro is well off 
the main streets are filled with latemodel us and mexican 
pickup trucks many bearing us license plates there are no 
beggars on the streets many of the homes and businesses were 
financed with dollars 
residents and public officials here say the law has helped those 
who hve been in the united states for a long time and wanted to 
stay there 
manuel sanchez returned several years ago and bought a butcher 
shop with the money he earned as an undocumented worker in chicago 
his brother a chicago butcher stayed and has applied for 
amnesty the provision of the law allowing foreigners who meet 
certain requirements to seek legal residency 
he feels a lot safer knowing that when he leaves the house in 
chicago hell return sanchez said 
illegal aliens caught in the united states most often are 
deported immediately 
for others who didnt qualify for amnesty under the law or just 
didnt bother to apply its business as usual a sundown trek 
across the border 
well stay as long as theres work when theres not well 
come back crying said jesus chavez 29 who has worked in the 
united states as an undocumented worker for a decade 
right now the work is there waiting for us said chavez one 
of three brothers working without documents at a california 
construction company 
chavez home on vacation said the 21 an hour he earns makes 
the risk of crossing as an illegal alien worthwhile 
similar work in mexico probably would pay him about 12 a day 
right now it the law hasnt affected us at all said luis 
chavez jesus 18yearold brother who began working illegally in 
the united states when he was 14 
the toughest provision of the us law went into effect this 
past june 1 making it illegal for most employers to knowingly hire 
undocumented workers the law calls for stiff fines and even jail 
sentences for violators 
agricultural workers now in the united states have been given an 
extension to dec 1 to get their papers in order or leave 
although crossing the border without legal documents is the 
risky part those whove worked in the same job in the united 
states since before 1982 dont have to show employers their 
documents 
</TEXT>
