editors note back in 1964 a man running for the white house 
could still bring his campaign to the people without a vast 
apparatus of hired imageshapers consultants security forces 
anxious glances at the latest quickie polls to tell him what to 
say perhaps one of the last candidates to present himself largely 
unencumbered was barry goldwater of arizona an ap reporter who 
covered this and many another run for the white house recalls how 
it felt in simpler times 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
barry goldwaters was the last of the freestyle presidential 
campaigns innocent of consultants short on security men played 
in person instead of on television and seldom inhibited by any 
real prospect of winning the white house 
that made it a perfect fit for the senator from arizona the 
secret service would have cramped his style and he undoubtedly 
would have fired the kind of campaign consultants who manage 
campaigns these days in 1964 goldwater worked with people he knew 
and trusted not hired hands he said what he thought which 
sometimes changed over the course of a campaign day he was accused 
of shooting from the hip but he wasnt always that careful 
for all that goldwaters 1964 campaign was candid generally 
honest short on rancor despite the bitterness of some of his most 
ardent supporters and remarkably prophetic 
latterday legend notwithstanding goldwater dug many of his own 
political traps before he became a presidential candidate his 
notions about selling tva and turning social security into a 
voluntary system are samples both proposals were made in pieces he 
wrote as mr conservative not mr candidate actually he tempered 
them during the campaign although he liked to reminisce about the 
blunt way hed talked in st petersburg about social security and 
in nashville about tva he repeated the proposals but he also said 
that he didnt believe in changing contracts like social security 
and that besides congress wouldnt let any president make that 
system voluntary or sell off tva 
it was a simpler time and too briefly a safer time john 
kennedy had been assassinated an event that deformed the politics 
of 1964 but that was an aberration secret service agents were not 
deployed around candidates until more than four years later after 
martin luther king and robert f kennedy had fallen to assassins 
goldwater traveled with charlie justice an automobile dealer 
hed met in a new hampshire motorcade as his sole security man 
during the presidential primaries since 1968 the secret service 
cocoon has enveloped candidates limiting access controlling 
crowds and often keeping voters away in the name of security 
not that goldwater was a gladhander he sometimes seemed 
annoyed when crowds kept him overtime one night an unexpected 
crowd of supporters turned up to cheer him as his chartered plane 
arrived in atlanta goldwater snapped a demand to know who on his 
staff was responsible for that 
im no babykissing backslapping blintzeleating 
politician he said one day in hanover nh that was intended as 
a slap at his arch rival new york gov nelson a rockefeller the 
eastern republican incarnate rocky of course delighted in being 
all of the above and like any new york politician he knew how to 
say blintz 
in concord an overzealous new hampshire supporter marched 
goldwater into the puritain restaurant to shake hands at lunch 
time the senator didnt stay long if somebody walked up to me 
while i was eating and stuck out his hand id put a hamburger in 
it goldwater said 
he was a westerner who liked guns security people do not like 
guns around their candidates one can only speculate at the 
reaction had the secret service been on hand when goldwater decided 
to fire a few shots across his driveway toward scottsdale into a 
bullet trap he sometimes missed he did just that one day after 
entertaining a group of reporters at lunch at his home one of them 
liked pistols as much as the senator did and goldwater invited him 
to join in target practice 
this proved exciting for the rest of the party still chatting 
with mrs goldwater when the gunfire began out of the front door 
one room away 
its just barry with his pistol said peggy goldwater 
thinking to calm her guests she made him stop shooting goldwater 
acknowledged it probably was just as well because some of his shots 
had strayed into the valley below and it seemed to bother the 
people at the church down there 
goldwater also liked airplanes as pilot and as passenger his 
campaign jet was named yia bi kin navajo for house in the sky 
it was one of the first of the boeing 727 jets that now are a 
staple of world aviation 
the senator flew it although nobody ever admitted that he also 
landed it when he arrived at dulles airport near washington after 
the election he brought it down hard and smiled knowingly when a 
reporter told him the third bounce landing was a nice one although 
the first had been rather exciting 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880815-0249 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
it was at least that exciting when the goldwater charter 
performed the bristol flyby early in the campaign the 727 took off 
from tri cities airport near bristol tenn and leveled off en 
route to cleveland suddenly the plane turned sharply and dove at 
high speed grown pilots and there were a lot in the goldwater 
entourage paled goldwater up front went into the cockpit and 
came back smiling the plane kept diving toward the ground then 
suddenly leveled off and blazed down the runway at control tower 
level a pilots prank 
that was to separate the men from the boys goldwater said 
consistency was not a hobgoblin of the goldwater campaign one 
morning in laconia nh during the primary campaign goldwater 
said he would be inclined to withdraw from the united nations if 
communist china were seated one stop later he said the united 
states must stay in the united nations another stop and he said 
that if the mainland chinese supplanted the nationalists it would 
blow us participation to pieces 
then that evening ive never said lets get out of the un 
i dont know how that rumor ever got started 
at an american legion convention in dallas goldwater likened 
the new york times to izvestia outside he chatted with a group of 
reporters and took pains to tell charles mohr the times reporter 
who covered his campaign that it wasnt personal i didnt mean 
you charlie i meant them he said 
goldwaters partisans despised reporters particularly eastern 
reporters a reporter for the san diego union arranged for two sets 
of press badges one read eastern liberal press the other read 
western tory press the safe course was to grab one of each 
the vietnam war was taking shape during 1964 the purported 
attack on us vessels in the gulf of tonkin came in august after 
goldwater had been nominated 
long before that happened goldwater warned that vietnam had the 
makings of the long agonizing conflict it became 
in an unlikely setting amid acres of blossoming pear orchards 
in northern california that spring goldwater said that vietnam 
could become a far more serious conflict than korea he said 
president lyndon b johnson should tell the nation of the peril 
and of his plans for the future 
at that time us involvement was limited to aid and advisers 
combat forces came later 
still grappling with the vietnam issue that fall goldwater 
announced that if elected he would ask former president dwight d 
eisenhower to go to south vietnam and recommend future policy 
it was an ironic echo of eisenhowers own promise in 1952 that 
if elected he would go to korea 
the problem was that nobody bothered to tell eisenhower what 
goldwater was about to propose 
goldwater never liked johnson and it only heightened his 
frustration at the democratic presidents landslide lead in polls 
borne out by the election besides the democratic president kept 
mousetrapping the republican nominee 
goldwater had voted against the civil rights act of 1964 that 
landmark law and the threat of a white backlash were backdrop 
realities during the campaign the senator said he didnt want them 
to become divisive issues a reporter asked whether he had talked 
with johnson about that concern goldwater hadnt but he would 
johnson grabbed that opening the instant he learned of it he 
said hed meet with goldwater any time they met at the white 
house on johnsons turf and johnsons terms johnsons people then 
crafted a joint statement which said in effect that the president 
would continue to take the high road on civil rights and the 
republcan nominee had finally agreed not to make an issue of it 
on election eve goldwater went north to his good luck town 
fredonia ariz on the utah border in indian country hed wound 
up his senate campaigns there and it would be the last stop on his 
presidential campaign too one reporter made it his mission to 
record for posterity the last words spoke in the campaign they 
were not memorable they were and if there are any paiutes out 
there i want to thank you too 
in 1964 the united states had seen three presidents 
eisenhower kennedy and johnson hold office within four years the 
voters werent about to install a fourth even had there been a 
republican nominee with wider support than goldwater found 
goldwater knew the odds when he hobbled into the campaign his foot 
in a cast after one bone spur surgery on election night 1964 at 
the camel back inn goldwaters staff set up a giant blackboard to 
record the popular and electoral vote state by state 
from the time the first votes were counted the johnson 
landslide was evident nobody bothered to write a number on the big 
blackboard chalk never touched it all night long 
</TEXT>
