<DOCNO> AP880815-0264 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
some professional birdwatchers look down on 
amateurs but the legacy of americas first ornithology professor 
unites their work 
cornell universitys laboratory of ornithology which owes its 
creation to arthur a allen contains millions of pages of behavior 
studies and photographs and the worlds largest collection of 
birdsongs more than 5000 species 
equally important it links ornithologists and amateur 
birdwatchers the game is to position the laboratory between the 
professional community and the birding community the amateur and 
the professional said executive director charles walcott we 
are an information broker between the two 
cornell is synonomous with ornithology in the minds of 
birdwatchers said elsa thompson copublisher of birdwatchers 
digest they are greatly respected as a technical and research 
facility 
but cornell has also managed to serve as a popular outreach 
helping bridge the gap between professional and amateur 
allen an expert on redwinged blackbirds and pioneer in 
recording and filming wild birds headed north americas only 
doctoral program in ornithology from the 1920s to the 40s he 
fashioned a firstrate program at cornell but it was lyman k 
stuart a business graduate who helped make the lab in sapsucker 
woods a 180acre sanctuary outside ithaca a reality 
stuart who won a life magazine contest with the bird 
photography allen taught him financed much of the construction 
the main building holds the largest collection of works by bird 
artist louis agassiz fuertes a floortoceiling window overlooks a 
10acre pond so visitors can watch feeder birds and waterfowl and 
listen to sounds piped in by microphones installed outside 
during allens lifetime he died in 1964 the laboratory 
gained international recognition but his continued connections 
with amateurs and volunteer conservationists were frowned upon by 
the new breed of professional ornithologists in response the 
university made the lab a separate department but without 
professors or course offerings and with no students of its own 
it was expected to support itself financially and generates 
money through dues and project fees sale of publications and bird 
recordings and homestudy courses in ornithology and bird 
photography 
membership dropped so low by 1980 that cornell seriously 
considered shutting down the lab walcott who earned a reputation 
as an educational promoter developing public television science 
shows like nova and 321 contact has boosted its 
membership from 2000 to 13000 in eight years and rejuventated its 
homestudy enrollment to about 9000 
now that we have become stable again we are turning our 
attention to our research efforts and producing a tremendous 
scientific archive he said of course all we do here has 
really one focus conservation the information we collect is 
highly useful as an environmental monitoring tool and we hope will 
serve as a biological early warning system 
its foremost study is in bioacoustics or bird communication 
with the help of computers we are making progress in finding out 
what birds say to each other and they do communicate said chris 
clark head of the program 
the research has led to similar efforts involving whales and 
elephants 
the labs 1yearold project feederwatch last year paid 4000 
backyard birdwatchers to fill out a computerized form twice weekly 
recording the species that appear at their feeders the goal this 
year is 10000 and walcott notes there are more than 82 million 
americans who put out food for wild birds 
we can only begin to guess at what we might have been able to 
accomplish if we had had this kind of information years ago he 
said how many extinct species we could have saved 
