<TEXT>
a west german scandal involving 
the use of illegal hormones to spur the growth of calves may spread 
to the netherlands and italy officials and news reports said 
monday 
discovery of the illegal hormone use has led to charges of an 
international hormone mafia and the arrest of a major veal 
producer in northwestern germany 
there is an illegal market for animal drugs that is causing 
mischief both within the european economic community and outside of 
it said klaus matthiesen agriculture minister for north 
rhinewestphalia 
the main substance at issue is testosterone the male hormone 
that is suspected of being a cancercausing agent in large doses 
authorities last week arrested veal producer felix hying of 
borken in the northwestern part of the country after discovering 
illegal hormone use hying was arrested on criminal charges of 
violating the countrys food and health laws that ban the use of 
hormones prosecutors say bernhard wigger another veal producer 
from the same area is suspected of using similar banned substances 
albert rentmeister a spokesman for the city of borken said 
wigger kept a thousand or more calves in the nearby netherlands 
siegfried martsch a spokesman for the environmentalist greens 
party in the affected state of north rhinewestphalia said 
there is a possibility wigger had business dealings with italy 
he did not reveal further details during a press conference in 
duesseldorf 
the hamburgbased der spiegel magazine and the westdeutsche 
rundfunk radio station of cologne said the hormones themselves came 
from the netherlands 
officials say they fear the scandal will grow 
matthiesen told reporters on sunday he is convinced there is an 
international hormone mafia behind the illegal use 
we have had many many indications not only in the last few 
days but also for several months that confirm this view the 
state minister said there are ties going beyond national 
boundaries 
west german offficials say its the largest hormone scandal in 
the countrys nearly 40year history 
the issue is particularly sensitive for west germans who are 
wary of food additives and similar substances 
health food firms also have been experiencing sharp growth in 
recent years while news accounts still chronicle the lingering 
effects of the 1986 chernobyl nuclear accident on the nations food 
supply 
matthiesen on friday ordered the confiscation of about 14000 
calves belonging to wigger because of the suspected use of 
testosterone 
testosterone is the principal male sex hormone and it is 
responsible for various male sex characteristics its use is banned 
throughout the european economic community 
wigger says that needle marks found on a sampling of his calves 
were only for routine immunizations 
also last week in a separate action north rhinewestphalia 
officials accused calf breeder hying of using testosterone on 
thousands of his calves 
officials ordered the slaughter of 4200 of hyings calves that 
tested postive for the hormone more than 10000 others were also 
being tested hying remained in jail monday afternoon pending 
further investigation 
local prosecutor klaus deupmann told reporters sunday that 500 
of the calves remained unaccounted for after several days of 
investigations 
we cant exclude the possibility that these calves have 
already been slaughtered prepared and have reached the markets 
deupmann added 
both wigger and hying have their businesses in towns located 
less than 10 kilometers six miles from the dutch border 
while experts say that testosterone is a suspected 
cancercausing agent west german scientists say that quantities of 
the substance found in the calves pose no danger to humans 
</TEXT>
