<TEXT>
the farm credit system on monday reported a 
profit for the second quarter continuing an improvement trend 
based on a reduction in its provision for loan losses 
the system said it had combined net income of 170 million for 
the quarter compared with a net loss of 46 million a year ago 
also contributing to the positive results were increased net 
interest income and a gain on the sales of certain properties 
the systems net interest income totaled 214 million compared 
with 110 million in the yearago period 
alan fass president and chief executive officer of the federal 
farm credit banks funding corp the financing arm of the farm 
credit system said improvements in net interest income resulted 
from increased reinstatements of nonaccrual loans to accrual status 
and from a modest decrease in the systems overall cost of debt 
when loans are placed on nonaccrual status they are accounted 
for only as they come in rather than when they are due 
during the second quarter the system reported negative 
provisions for loan losses of 181 million compared with a 
negative provision of 10 million a year earlier 
in spite of the current drought the recent improvements in 
the agricultural economy continued throughout the second quarter 
resulting in stabilized loan collateral values and other 
improvements in the overall credit quality of the systems loan 
portfolio fass said 
he noted that while it is too early to assess the impact of the 
current drought on system institutions the system has been 
monitoring the drought very closely because of its potential impact 
on borrowers in certain parts of the country 
for the first six months the system reported net income of 336 
million compared with a loss of 201 million a year ago net 
interest income during the period totaled 360 million up from 
258 million a year ago 
during the second half the system reported negative provisions 
for loan losses of 341 million compared with a provision of 105 
million a year earlier 
the farm credit system consists of 37 borrowerowned banks and 
associations serving the rural economy congress put it on a more 
secure footing last year by authorizing the issuance of up to 4 
billion in governmentbacked lowinterest loans the 1987 
legislation by increasing confidence in the farm credit system 
made it possible to narrow the interestrate spreads on farm credit 
debt obligations over us treasury securities 
</TEXT>
