<TEXT>
a federal judge on monday dismissed lawsuit 
allegations that top media general corp officials had an 
obligation to consider an unsolicited merger offer from investor 
burt sugarman 
but us district judge richard l williams refused to throw out 
suit allegations that media general made misleading statements in a 
recent proxy fight and that its board of directors may have acted 
improperly in creating a twotiered stock structure that makes 
takeovers impossible without the consent of top management 
the allegations were contained in two lawsuits filed by 
stockholders against the richmondbased media company after 
sugarman made a 18 billion buyout offer for the companys class a 
stock in late february 
media general repeatedly rebuffed the overtures by sugarman who 
staged an unsuccessful proxy fight for three seats on the board of 
directors in may 
media general chairman d tennant bryan and his family own 71 
percent of the companys class b shares which control the election 
of the other six board members bryan has said the familys 
interest is not for sale 
sugarman failed in a lawsuit to get a ruling allowing a combined 
class a and b shareholders majority vote on the takeover offer 
and was critical of the companys twotier stock structure 
on monday williams told the plaintiffs in the shareholder suits 
that they should be prepared to show him at a sept 8 pretrial 
meeting that their cases should go to a jury 
for some time now the court has suspected that both were filed 
with the thought in mind that if sugarman was successful on his 
claims the other shareholders might reap a corresponding 
windfall the judge said 
stockholders harry m jasper of new york and sarah shields of 
florida filed one of the suits contending they paid too much for 
their media general stock because the price was inflated by 
incomplete or misleading statements by some of the companys top 
officers 
ms shields and jasper also claimed the bryans had a fiduciary 
duty to investigate and consider sugarmans merger plan and a later 
restructuring proposal 
but williams noted the bryans also are the principal 
stockholders in addition to being directors 
once the bryans as controlling shareholders had firmly 
rejected sugarmans offer the board of directors had practically 
no role to play with respect to the sugarman offer the judge 
said 
the bryans duty as directors does not obliterate their right 
as shareholders to sell or not to sell their stock as they 
choose said williams 
the second suit was filed by kenneth rosenthal who said the 
bryans as principal shareholders had a duty to other 
shareholders williams dimissed that part of rosenthals suit 
saying virginia law made no such requirement 
</TEXT>
