<TEXT>
some 1700 hospital service workers at 
seven hospitals overwhelmingly approved a twoyear contract monday 
while more than 2000 striking nurses from six of the same 
hospitals returned to the bargaining table 
despite ratification the agreement calls for members of local 
250 of the hospital and health care workers union to remain off the 
job until the california nurses association ratifies an accord 
but union leaders this weekend indicated it was not certain they 
would enforce that provision if the nurses dispute continues for 
more than a few days 
the service workers union reported 92 percent of its members 
voted for ratification of a contract which was reached in a 
60hour negotiating session under the auspices of mayor art agnos 
and a federal mediator 
the union said it struck a compromise over sick time and 
vacation days and eliminated plans by the hospitals to require 
workers to pay a share of the basic health insurance plan it also 
said the twoyear agreement restored fringe benefits for both 
fulltime and parttime workers 
on wages the licensed vocational nurses will get a 3 percent 
increase over two years going from 1205 an hour to 1240 an 
hour the technical classes will get 1225 by the end of the 
contract employees at the lower end of a twotier wage system will 
get 3 percent increases in each of the two years 
service and maintenance workers who account for 45 percent of 
union membership will get no raise but lumpsum bonuses of up to 
300 by the end of the pact 
it was the first strike for local 250 in 50 years 
talks between the affiliated hospitals management group and the 
california nurses association were renewed sunday also assisted by 
agnos and the mediator 
the service workers accord raised hopes for a quick end to the 
labor problems that have hobbled eight hospitals for nearly a month 
the major issues in the nurses strike which started aug 2 
include demands for big salary increases overtime pay for weekend 
work and staffing improvements the nurses object to a management 
demand for the right to impose 12hour workdays 
local 250s members include vocational nurses surgical and 
psychiatric technicians dietary workers janitors and housekeeping 
employees pay currently ranges from 790 an hour for lowertier 
housekeeping laundry and and food service workers and hospital 
aides to 1190 hourly for technicians and licensed vocational 
nurses 
within a day of the tentative agreement talks with the 
registered nurses began but eileen maloney a spokesman for agnos 
cautioned against hopes for an immediate settlement 
the average salary for a nurse working for one of the affiliated 
hospitals ranges between 30072 and 37692 for day shifts and 
34583 to 43346 for night shift nurses 
hospitals hit by the strike have employed nurses from around the 
country as replacements the replacements are being recruited with 
promises of hourly wages ranging between 20 and 25 an hour plus 
free air fare and accommodations while in san francisco 
the cna said the high cost of hiring replacements was applying 
great pressure on the hospitals to settle quickly 
the affiliated hospitals group represents childrens marshal 
hale mount zion st francis and st marys in san francisco and 
seton medical center in daly city nurses also are on strike at 
french hospital where talks are being held separately 
the service workers union are on strike at the same hospitals 
plus pacific presbyterian medical center where the registered 
nurses are not unionized 
</TEXT>
